<% content_for :title, "How It Works – Dark Factory" %>

<div class="info-page">
  <nav class="info-nav">
    <%= link_to "← Back to board", root_path %>
  </nav>

  <h1 class="info-title">How Dark Factory Works</h1>
  <p class="info-subtitle">
    Dark Factory is a self-building Rails application — you describe a feature,
    and AI agents write the code, open a pull request, and review their own work,
    all without you touching a keyboard.
  </p>

  <!-- ── SECTION 1: The Big Picture ── -->
  <section class="info-section">
    <h2 class="info-section__heading">The Big Picture</h2>
    <p class="info-section__lead">
      Think of Dark Factory as a software team that never sleeps. You are the product manager:
      you write what you want. The agents are the engineers and reviewers: they figure out how
      to build it, make the changes, and check each other's work.
    </p>

    <div class="info-steps">
      <div class="info-step">
        <span class="info-step__num">1</span>
        <div>
          <strong>You submit a feature request</strong> — a short title and a plain-English
          description of what you want built.
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="info-step">
        <span class="info-step__num">2</span>
        <div>
          <strong>An AI agent reads your request</strong> and writes the code, editing files
          directly inside the project. You can watch every move in real time.
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="info-step">
        <span class="info-step__num">3</span>
        <div>
          <strong>The agent opens a pull request</strong> on GitHub with all the changes, then
          a second agent reviews the code against your original description.
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="info-step">
        <span class="info-step__num">4</span>
        <div>
          <strong>If changes are needed</strong>, a third agent reads the review feedback and
          updates the code automatically. Once everything looks good, you merge.
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── SECTION 2: What "Dark Factory" Means ── -->
  <section class="info-section">
    <h2 class="info-section__heading">What Does "Dark Factory" Mean?</h2>
    <p>
      In manufacturing, a <em>dark factory</em> is a fully automated plant that runs entirely
      in the dark — no human workers, no lights needed. Machines handle everything from raw
      material to finished product.
    </p>
    <p>
      This app borrows the same idea for software: once you submit a request the lights go out
      and the agents take over. They read the codebase, write the code, commit it, push it,
      and open a pull request — all without anyone in the loop. The only human step is
      reviewing and merging the finished PR.
    </p>
    <div class="info-callout">
      <strong>Fun detail:</strong> Dark Factory can improve itself. Submit a feature request
      asking for a new capability, and the agents will implement it in their own codebase and
      open a PR against the same repo you are looking at right now.
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── SECTION 3: Meet the Agents ── -->
  <section class="info-section">
    <h2 class="info-section__heading">Meet the Three Agents</h2>
    <p>
      Each agent is a Claude AI model given a specific job and a set of tools
      (read files, write files, run shell commands, call the GitHub API). They work in
      isolated copies of the repository so they can never break each other's work.
    </p>

    <div class="info-agents">
      <div class="info-agent info-agent--implement">
        <div class="info-agent__icon">🏗️</div>
        <div class="info-agent__body">
          <h3 class="info-agent__name">Implementation Agent</h3>
          <p class="info-agent__desc">
            The builder. It reads your feature request, explores the codebase to understand
            how it works, writes or edits the files it needs to change, and commits the result.
            When it is done it pushes the branch and opens a pull request on GitHub.
          </p>
          <ul class="info-agent__facts">
            <li>Triggered automatically when you submit a request</li>
            <li>Works in an isolated git worktree (a private sandbox)</li>
            <li>Every tool call — file read, file write, shell command — is streamed live to your browser</li>
            <li>If it cannot make at least one commit, the request is marked <em>Failed</em></li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="info-agent info-agent--review">
        <div class="info-agent__icon">🔍</div>
        <div class="info-agent__body">
          <h3 class="info-agent__name">Review Agent</h3>
          <p class="info-agent__desc">
            The quality checker. It reads the pull request diff, compares it against your
            original description, and posts a formal GitHub review: either an approval or a
            list of requested changes with specific comments.
          </p>
          <ul class="info-agent__facts">
            <li>Fires automatically after the Implementation Agent opens a PR</li>
            <li>Posts a real GitHub PR review (Approved or Changes Requested)</li>
            <li>If it requests changes, the card moves to the <em>Review Feedback</em> column</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="info-agent info-agent--address">
        <div class="info-agent__icon">🛠️</div>
        <div class="info-agent__body">
          <h3 class="info-agent__name">Feedback Agent</h3>
          <p class="info-agent__desc">
            The fixer. When the Review Agent asks for changes, this agent reads every comment,
            makes the necessary edits, commits them, and pushes to the same PR branch so the
            review can be re-evaluated.
          </p>
          <ul class="info-agent__facts">
            <li>Triggered automatically when a <em>Changes Requested</em> review is detected</li>
            <li>Edits the existing PR branch in place — no new branch created</li>
            <li>Runs at most once per feature request to prevent infinite loops</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── SECTION 4: The Kanban Board ── -->
  <section class="info-section">
    <h2 class="info-section__heading">Reading the Kanban Board</h2>
    <p>
      The home page shows every feature request as a card on a Kanban board. Each column
      represents a stage in the pipeline:
    </p>

    <div class="info-columns">
      <div class="info-col info-col--todo">
        <strong>Todo</strong>
        <span>Waiting to be picked up by the Implementation Agent.</span>
      </div>
      <div class="info-col info-col--doing">
        <strong>Doing</strong>
        <span>An agent is actively working right now. Watch the live event stream on the detail page.</span>
      </div>
      <div class="info-col info-col--to_review">
        <strong>To Review</strong>
        <span>A pull request is open on GitHub. The Review Agent has run (or is running). Waiting for a human merge.</span>
      </div>
      <div class="info-col info-col--review_feedback">
        <strong>Review Feedback</strong>
        <span>The Review Agent asked for changes. The Feedback Agent will address them automatically.</span>
      </div>
      <div class="info-col info-col--failed">
        <strong>Failed</strong>
        <span>Something went wrong. Open the card to read the error, then delete it and resubmit with a clearer description.</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── SECTION 5: Tips ── -->
  <section class="info-section">
    <h2 class="info-section__heading">Tips for Good Feature Requests</h2>
    <ul class="info-tips">
      <li>
        <strong>Be specific.</strong> Instead of "improve the UI", try
        "add a character count below the body textarea that turns red when over 500 characters."
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>One thing at a time.</strong> Smaller, focused requests succeed more often than
        large multi-part ones.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Describe the goal, not the implementation.</strong> Tell the agent what the
        feature should do for the user, not which files to edit — it will figure that out.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Check the event stream</strong> on the detail page to see exactly what the agent
        did. If it misunderstood something, the stream usually shows where it went off track.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <div class="info-footer">
    <%= link_to "← Back to board", root_path, class: "info-footer__link" %>
    <%= link_to "FAQ", faq_path, class: "info-footer__link" %>
  </div>
</div>
